Remove the Accessors and Mutators for the Deleted Parallel Lists
Recall that accessors and mutators were implemented for each of a Room’s instance variables. Since the lists exitLocations and itemDescriptions were removed, their respective accessors and mutators must also be removed. The existing accessors and mutators for the instance variables exits and items remain unchanged. In fact, they will work seamlessly with the new dictionaries.
The accessor and mutator for the old instance variable exitLocations must be removed from the source code:
# remove these two functions
@property
def exitLocations(self):
    return self._exitLocations

@exitLocations.setter
def exitLocations(self, value):
    self._exitLocations = value
The accessor and mutator for the old instance variable itemDescriptions must also be removed from the source code:
# remove these two functions
@property
def itemDescriptions(self):
    return self._itemDescriptions

@itemDescriptions.setter
def itemDescriptions(self, value):
    self._itemDescriptions = value

Modify the addExit and addItem Functions
The next step is to change the addExit and addItem functions in the Room class so that they appropriately insert new exits and items into dictionaries instead of parallel lists as is currently done. First, let’s change the addExit function:
class Room:
    # the rest of the code omitted for brevity

    def addExit(self, exit, room):
        self._exits.append(exit)            # remove this line
        self._exitLocations.append(room)    # remove this line
Note how the function currently appends the exit to one list and the room to another. Let’s change this so that the exit and room are added as a key-value pair to the appropriate dictionary:
class Room:
    # the rest of the code omitted for brevity

    def addExit(self, exit, room):
        # append the exit and room to the appropriate dictionary
        self._exits[exit] = room    # add this line
Now, let’s change the addItem function:
class Room:
    # the rest of the code omitted for brevity

    def addItem(self, item, desc):
        # append the item and description to the appropriate lists
        self._items.append(item)            # remove this line
        self._itemDescriptions.append(desc) # remove this line
This function is similar to the old addExit function. It appends the item to one list and the description to another. Let’s change this so that the item and description are added as a key-value pair to the appropriate dictionary:
class Room:
    # the rest of the code omitted for brevity

    def addItem(self, item, desc):
        # append the item and description to the appropriate dictionary
        self._items[item] = desc    # add this line

Getters and Setters
If you had getters and setter in the previous iteration, let’s omit the ones that are not being used for any special checking of values. In the academic world, we ask you to create getters and setters that do nothing just to make sure you know how to. However, now that we’ve mastered that concept, we will only include the necessary ones.
That leaves us with one single pair of getters and setters, which will be for our image instance variable. We will use the setter to check if the image exists in the filesystem. If it doesn’t it will throw an error. This will be for our own purposes for when we instantiate rooms later on. That is, if we create a room where the filepath doesn’t exist for the image, we will know immediately.
To do this, be sure to import the os module at the top of your file.
# room.py

import os

class Room:
    # construtor omitted for brevity

    # getters and setters for the instance variables
    @property
    def image(self):
        return self._image

    @image.setter
    def image(self, value):
        # check if filepath exists
        if not os.path.exists(value):
            # raise an error to kill the program if it does not
            raise ValueError(f"Filepath does not exist: {value}")

        # at this point, if we haven't hit the error, set the filepath
        self._image = value
